Test data for --lsp with HLS (Haskell Language Server).

Prerequisites:
  - GHCup:  curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://get-ghcup.haskell.org | sh
  - HLS:    ghcup install hls
  - Build:  cd tests/lsp/haskell && cabal build

Known limitation: the Haskell tree-sitter grammar cannot parse ($X :: Int)
patterns because :: is ambiguous with the list cons operator when $X is a
semgrep metavar. This means TypedMetavar patterns (which trigger LSP hover
queries) don't work yet. The LSP hover parsing infrastructure (clean_hover,
parse_type) is ready and will work once the grammar is fixed.

The metavariable-type: rule key works for static type matching:

  # /tmp/test.yaml
  rules:
    - id: test-int
      patterns:
        - pattern: $X
        - metavariable-type:
            metavariable: $X
            type: Int
      languages: [haskell]
      message: "Found Int: $X"
      severity: WARNING

  osemgrep scan --config /tmp/test.yaml tests/lsp/haskell/Main.hs

Note: osemgrep automatically finds the project root (directory containing
*.cabal) by walking upward from the target file. This is needed
because HLS requires the workspace root.

Note: HLS needs warm-up time to load the GHC session. Use --timeout 30
(or higher) to avoid the default 5-second per-file timeout.

Note: HLS wrapper uses CWD to discover the project cradle, so the
server_cmd uses "cd <root> && haskell-language-server-wrapper --lsp".
